      },
      "date": "2019-04-17 14:15:26.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n>Have you looked at the implementation of enc_pools in lustre/ptlrpc/sec_bulk.c? Allocating contiguous pages is very much like what enc_pools are made for. Maybe the code for enc_pools should be moved (and renamed?) so that it can be used for compression, but we may try to avoid duplicating what is already available.\n\nSebastien, yes, we have looked at enc_pool from the beginning and wished to use it. But if I remember correctly, it's all about the bulk desc, which is not yet existent at the point we hook in with compression. We've seen some useful functionality, but allover it was too complex and closely connected to the GSS layer. We would need to change a lot and did not want to depend on it.\nFor any progress and a proof of concept it seemed to be easier to implement our demands in a separate pool. \nThis discussion can maybe explain some points https://marc.info/?l=lustre-devel&m=150065013617747&w=2\nWe have to see how our approach works out.\nIn the long term, it is surely desirable to have one pool for both or at least reduce duplicates (if present). \nDid the enc_pool reserved fix sized contiguous page bundles for free usage like we do?\n\n>Also, is this code CPT aware?\n\nWe hope the pool to be thread safe, we are still testing. Error handling is missing anyway.\nI'm not sure what CPT aware means.\n\n>I like to add the kernel has a implementation called zbud which is very much like this work.\n\nJames, I am very unfamiliar with zbud, but what I understood from its description, it is not really helpful for our purpose. When I am right, zbud composes two strong compressed pages to one physical page. This is nice when you do page-to-page compression like zram. But we are aiming for buffer-to-buffer compression, not a single page. Although we need additional buffers for compression processing and have copy efforts, we win much higher entropy and optimally full pages in chunks. For those buffers we need this pool. Maybe I'm currently not able to identify the overlaps, please correct me if it is the case.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1e54146cdbda6da46a51c004f7f43ceaa73119da",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 597,
        "name": "Sebastien Buisson",
        "email": "sbuisson@ddn.com",
        "username": "sbuisson"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-19 08:16:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nMy concerns about implementing this page pool are:\n\na) do we need to make it available for encryption as well? The question arises from the fact that we cannot encrypt data in-place in the page cache, since the cached plaintext must be preserved. Instead, we must encrypt into a temporary buffer or \"bounce page\", then write out the temporary buffer. The good news is fscrypt is taking care of the bounce page allocation via a page pool of its own, so we will not have to handle this page allocation at the Lustre level;\n\nb) can we re-use what already exists with Lustre enc_pools? After looking at enc_pools implementation, it seems to be tightly coupled to GSS usage, so it would need to be made more generic. Also, I was wrong in assuming that enc_pools mechanism was allocating contiguous pages. Pages are located one by one by calling alloc_page(). So it would need other modifications to allow requesting for contiguous pages.\n\n\nHowever, enc_pools mechanism has important features that this implementation for compression lacks in this version:\n\n1) wait queue in case of not enough free pages. This is not really acceptable to sleep for an arbitrary amount of time, like wait-For_mem() does;\n\n2) usage statistics. Knowing cache access/miss, grow/shrink, requests, etc would make much sense for debugging purpose and also when compression is used in production.\n\n\nSo, to sum up my thoughts, after examining a) and b) I would tend to think that you could go ahead with this compression specific implementation of a page pool, but that would require to get inspiration from enc_pools implementation, in particular to address remarks 1) and 2).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "bfa89a683230cfd232c60877dbb5c79f33b496df",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 743,
        "name": "Anna Fuchs",
        "email": "anna.fuchs@informatik.uni-hamburg.de",
        "username": "fuchs"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-25 09:57:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nPoints 1 and 2 are about performance optimization. It will come in the second part of my research work.\nOnce the first memory request is rejected, we have, I would say, three possibilities how to react.\n1) just wait a bit, what we are currently doing (prioritized waiting should be possible, but not mandatory)\n2) cancel compression of the particular chunk/stripe/bulk and proceed with uncompressed piece of data\n3) grow the pool\nWe are not aiming to make the pool growable (or shrinkable), but static and preallocated before the system runs.\nSince we have potentially big contiguous blocks (ZFS record size can be up to 1MiB), the chance to allocate such blocks under system load is very low.\nIn the thread I have linked we have already discussed how to figure out the best pool size. This has to be examined very accurately (balance client's memory for computation and compression; how to deal with additional OSTs, etc), but for the first its size will be static.\nSo we can choose between cancelling and waiting. In my research work I plan to introduce some smart and flexible strategies depending on our test results. But all that is future work.\n\nRegarding enc_pool, it soudns like encryption has other demands. The pool does not offer what we need and enc does not need what we offer. Might be needles to combine them at any price. At least not yet.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1c38b78a788926b81f28a32cf7503c8d07bd2099",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-25 13:00:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nWill you be at LUG? If so we should me and discuss this work.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "16d2fb10f19e4575abd45c7dedaf560c55566c2e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 743,
        "name": "Anna Fuchs",
        "email": "anna.fuchs@informatik.uni-hamburg.de",
        "username": "fuchs"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-25 14:18:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nNo. Probably at LAD.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "76dc1098a7edccf6585e4992c16eddfc82c8f7aa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-25 18:01:13.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nHow did of buffers are we talking here? If you allocating a large amount of contiguous pages the change of failing to allocate are really high.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "37cafc62bf0b541d6319e8d83e0052fec3e42ff1",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 797,
        "name": "Patrick Farrell",
        "email": "pfarrell@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "pfarrell",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2019-04-25 18:51:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nJames,\n\nThis is addressed in Anna's recent comments.  (Up to 1 MiB, but at startup time, for that reason.  I refer you to her comments for the rest. :) )",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "d80c7d6ffe9cbd46fbcf47be874558b77939e7c2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-25 19:06:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nOkay wasn't so clear in the comments. Hmm. I see the way this is handled in the crypto layer is with vmalloc(). See linux/crypto/lz4hc.c.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "a8cd75e842fc60edced723899e58d95c059834c7",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-26 06:36:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nUsing kvmalloc() is the preferred method for large buffers (over 8-16KB).  It is fast if such buffers are available continuously, but doesn't fail if the memory is fragmented.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "7d65deca5109d1c4314ff6f8ebcccc1b818a0452",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 743,
        "name": "Anna Fuchs",
        "email": "anna.fuchs@informatik.uni-hamburg.de",
        "username": "fuchs"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-26 11:48:25.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nThe compressor requires virtually contiguous memory. We afford the luxury to have physically contiguous pages here and that, we believe, for a low price. When using only virtually contig. memory like Linux provides via vmalloc, you can be pretty sure to get what you need, even huge blocks. Therefore, you might be able to use it dynamically under system load, let the pool grow and shrink. Due to lower performance permanent vmallocing during the system run becomes more expensive. So here the decision to prepare everything from the beginning -- we hope the memory not to be very much fragmented then. I believe accessing physically contig. memory performs better than virt. \nWe used alloc_pages to have a more comfortable handling when requesting a page array instead of page buffer (we have another compression algorithm which can handle page arrays to save one buffer copy). Otherwise, kvmalloc might be our choice. Once we really wanted to make the pool growable, we might go with vmalloc for the dynamic part and keep the core pool kmalloced. We might change it later when benchmarking everything.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "1e2415e95e7ea11f12b8da37f8990df4f34195aa",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-04-26 23:39:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nOne problem we had with large kmalloc() \"at startup\" is that this works if the system is newly booted, but fails if the client or server is inmounted and remounted without a reboot. That can happen during service or upgrading the RPMs.  Some very large nodes can take tens of minutes to reboot if they have large numbers of disks, CPUs, RAM, PCI cards, etc. so it is best not to require a reboot for that to work.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
